preferred-citation:
  type: article
  title: "Exploratory MPAS Sensitivity Experiments on Rainforest Biogenic Salt Aerosols, Tropical Rainfall, and Poleward Moisture Transport"
  authors:
    - family-names: "Lue"
      given-names: "Brian"
      email: "bluesaltbarrier@gmail.com"
      affiliation: "Independent researcher"
  year: 2026
  month: 4
  journal: "EarthArxiv"
  doi: "10.31223/TODO-EARTHARXIV-DOI"
  url: "https://eartharxiv.org/repository/view/TODO/"
  abstract: >
    Rainforest ecosystems emit biologically influenced aerosol particles,
    including potassium-rich and other hygroscopic components that may
    affect warm-rain microphysics. We present exploratory sensitivity
    experiments using MPAS-Atmosphere to test whether rainforest biogenic
    salt aerosol parameterizations can alter modeled tropical precipitation
    and large-scale moisture-transport diagnostics. Across ten single-
    member 30-day implementations, diagnosed latent-heat transport at
    30 N varies substantially; the sign of the Amazon rainfall response
    depends on baseline aerosol loading, consistent with regime-dependent
    aerosol-cloud theory. The results motivate follow-up using convection-
    permitting ensembles, observational constraints on rainforest aerosol
    emissions, and higher-fidelity cloud microphysics.

